#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:3
msgid "The meta.yaml specification"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:5
msgid ""
"Packages are defined by writing a `meta.yaml` file. The format of these "
"files is based on the `meta.yaml` files used to build [Conda packages]"
"(https://docs.conda.io/projects/conda-build/en/latest/resources/define-"
"metadata.html), though it is much more limited. The most important "
"limitation is that Pyodide assumes there will only be one version of a given "
"library available, whereas Conda allows the user to specify the versions of "
"each package that they want to install. Despite the limitations, it is "
"recommended to use existing conda package definitions as a starting point to "
"create Pyodide packages. In general, however, one should not expect Conda "
"packages to \"just work\" with Pyodide, see {pr}`795`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:16
msgid "This is unstable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:19
msgid ""
"The Pyodide build system is under fairly active development (as of "
"2022/03/13). The next couple of releases are likely to include breaking "
"changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:23
msgid "The supported keys in the `meta.yaml` file are described below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:25
msgid "`package`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:27
msgid "`package/name`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:29
msgid ""
"The name of the package. It must match the name of the package used when "
"expanding the tarball, which is sometimes different from the name of the "
"package in the Python namespace when installed. It must also match the name "
"of the directory in which the `meta.yaml` file is placed. It can only "
"contain alphanumeric characters, `-`, and `_`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:35
msgid "`package/version`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:37
msgid "The version of the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:39
msgid "`package/top-level`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:41
msgid ""
"The list of top-level import name for the package. This key is used in {js:"
"func}`pyodide.loadPackagesFromImports`. For example, the top-level import "
"name for the `scikit-learn` is `sklearn`. Some packages may have multiple "
"top-level import names. For instance, `setuptools` exposes `setuptools` and "
"`pkg_resources` as a top-level import names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:48
msgid "`package/tag`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:50
msgid ""
"The list of tags of the package. This is meta information used to group "
"packages by functionality. Normally this is not needed. The following tags "
"are currently used in Pyodide, for better CI grouping or for testing "
"purposes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:55
msgid "always: This package is always built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:56
msgid "core: This package is used in the Pyodide core test suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:57
msgid ""
"min-scipy-stack: This package is part of the minimal Scientific Python stack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:58
msgid "library: This package is a shared or static library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:59
msgid "shared_library: This package is a shared library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:60
msgid "static_library: This package is a static library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:61
msgid "pyodide-test: This package is used to test the Pyodide build system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:62
msgid "rust: This package requires a Rust toolchain to build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:64
msgid "`source`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:66
msgid "`source/url`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:68
msgid "The URL of the source tarball."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:70
msgid ""
"The tarball may be in any of the formats supported by Python's {py:func}"
"`shutil.unpack_archive`: `tar`, `gztar`, `bztar`, `xztar`, and `zip`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:73
msgid "`source/extract_dir`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:75
msgid ""
"The top level directory name of the contents of the source tarball (i.e. "
"once you extract the tarball, all the contents are in the directory named "
"`source/extract_dir`). This defaults to the tarball name (sans extension)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:79
msgid "`source/path`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:81
msgid ""
"Alternatively to `source/url`, a relative or absolute path can be specified "
"as package source. This is useful for local testing or building packages "
"which are not available online in the required format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:85
msgid "If a path is specified, any provided checksums are ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:87
msgid "`source/sha256`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:89
msgid ""
"The SHA256 checksum of the tarball. It is recommended to use SHA256 instead "
"of MD5. At most one checksum entry should be provided per package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:92
msgid "`source/patches`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:94
msgid ""
"A list of patch files to apply after expanding the tarball. These are "
"applied using `patch -p1` from the root of the source tree."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:97
msgid "`source/extras`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:99
msgid ""
"Extra files to add to the source tree. This should be a list where each "
"entry is a pair of the form `(src, dst)`. The `src` path is relative to the "
"directory in which the `meta.yaml` file resides. The `dst` path is relative "
"to the root of source tree (the expanded tarball)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:104
msgid "`build`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:106
msgid "`build/cflags`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:108
msgid "Extra arguments to pass to the compiler when building for WebAssembly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:110 ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:119
#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:125
msgid "(This key is not in the Conda spec)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:112
msgid "`build/cxxflags`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:114
msgid ""
"Extra arguments to pass to the compiler when building C++ files for "
"WebAssembly. Note that both `cflags` and `cxxflags` will be used when "
"compiling C++ files. A common example would be to use `-std=c++11` for code "
"that makes use of C++11 features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:121
msgid "`build/ldflags`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:123
msgid "Extra arguments to pass to the linker when building for WebAssembly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:127
msgid "`build/exports`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:129
msgid ""
"Which symbols should be exported from the shared object files. Possible "
"values are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:132
msgid ""
"`pyinit`: The default. Only export Python module initialization symbols of "
"the form `PyInit_some_module`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:134
msgid ""
"`requested`: Export the functions that are marked as exported in the object "
"files. Switch to this if `pyinit` doesn't work. Useful for packages that use "
"`ctypes` or `dlsym` to access symbols."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:137
msgid ""
"`whole_archive`: Uses `-Wl,--whole-archive` to force inclusion of all "
"symbols. Use this when neither `pyinit` nor `explicit` work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:140
msgid "`build/backend-flags`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:142
msgid ""
"Extra flags to pass to the build backend (e.g., `setuptools`, `flit`, etc)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:144
msgid "`build/type`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:146
msgid "Type of the package. Possible values are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:148
msgid "package (default): A normal Python package, built to a wheel file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:149
msgid "static_library: A static library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:150
msgid "shared_library: A shared library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:151
msgid ""
"cpython_module: A CPython stdlib extension module. This is used for "
"unvendoring CPython modules, and should not be used for other purposes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:155
msgid ""
"If you are building ordinary Python package, you don't need to set this key. "
"But if you are building a static or shared library, you need to set this to "
"`static_library` or `shared_library` respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:159
msgid ""
"Static and shared libraries are not Python packages themselves, but are "
"needed for other Python packages. For libraries, the script specified in the "
"`build/script` section is run to compile the library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:164
msgid ""
"The difference between `static_library` and `shared_library` is that "
"`static_library` is statically linked into the other packages, so it is "
"required only in the build time, while `shared_library` is dynamically "
"linked, so it is required in the runtime. When building a shared library, "
"you should copy the built libraries into the `$DISTDIR`. Files or folders in "
"this folder will be packaged to make the Pyodide package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:171
msgid ""
"See the [zlib meta.yaml](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide/blob/main/"
"packages/zlib/meta.yaml) for an example of a static library specification, "
"and the [OpenBLAS meta.yaml](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide/blob/main/"
"packages/openblas/meta.yaml) for an example of a shared library "
"specification."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:177
msgid "`build/script`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:179
msgid ""
"The script section is required for a library package (`build/library` set to "
"true). For a Python package this section is optional. If it is specified for "
"a Python package, the script section will be run before the build system "
"runs `setup.py`. This script is run by `bash` in the directory where the "
"tarball was extracted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:185
msgid "There are special environment variables defined:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:187
msgid "`$PKGDIR`: The directory in which the `meta.yaml` file resides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:188
msgid "`$PKG_VESRION`: The version of the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:189
msgid "`$PKG_BUILD_DIR`: The directory where the tarball was extracted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:190
msgid ""
"`$DISTDIR`: The directory where the built wheel or library should be placed. "
"If you are building a shared library, you should copy the built libraries "
"into this directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:194
msgid "(These keys are not in the Conda spec)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:196
msgid "`build/cross-script`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:198
msgid ""
"This script will run _after_ `build/script`. The difference is that it runs "
"with the target environment variables and `sysconfigdata` and with the "
"`pywasmcross` compiler symlinks. Any changes to the environment will persist "
"to the main build step but will not be seen in the `build/post` step (or "
"anything else done outside of the cross build environment). The working "
"directory for this script is the source directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:205
msgid "`build/post`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:207
msgid ""
"Shell commands to run after building the package. This command runs in the "
"directory which contains the built wheel unpacked with `python -m wheel "
"unpack`. So it's possible to manually add, delete, change, move files etc. "
"See the [setuptools meta.yaml](https://github.com/pyodide/pyodide/ blob/main/"
"packages/setuptools/meta.yaml) for an example of the usage of this key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:214
msgid "`build/unvendor-tests`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:216
msgid ""
"Whether to unvendor tests found in the installation folder to a separate "
"package `<package-name>-tests`. If this option is true and no tests are "
"found, the test package will not be created. Default: true."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:220
msgid "`build/vendor-sharedlib`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:222
msgid ""
"If set to true, shared libraries that are required by the package will be "
"vendored into the package after the build. This is similar to what "
"[`auditwheel repair`](https://github.com/pypa/auditwheel) does, but it is "
"done in a way that is compatible with Pyodide and Emscripten dynamic "
"linking. Default: false."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:228
msgid "`requirements`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:230
msgid "`requirements/run`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:232
msgid "A list of required packages at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:234
msgid "(Unlike conda, this only supports package names, not versions)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:236
msgid "`requirements/host`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:238
msgid ""
"A list of Pyodide packages that are required when building a package. It "
"represents packages that need to be specific to the target platform."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:240
msgid ""
"For instance, when building `libxml`, `zlib` needs to be built for WASM "
"first, and so it's a host dependency. This is unrelated to the fact that the "
"build system might already have `zlib` present."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:243
msgid "`requirements/executable`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:245
msgid "A list of executables that are required when building a package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:247
msgid ""
"Note that unlike conda, specifying executables in this key doesn't actually "
"install any of them. This key exists to halt build earlier if required "
"executables are not available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:251
msgid "`test`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:253
msgid "`test/imports`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:255
msgid "List of imports to test after the package is built."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:257
msgid "Supported Environment Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:259
msgid ""
"The following environment variables can be used in the scripts in the meta."
"yaml files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:262
msgid "PYODIDE_ROOT: The path to the base Pyodide directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:263
msgid "PYMAJOR: Current major Python version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:264
msgid "PYMINOR: Current minor Python version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:265
msgid "PYMICRO: Current micro Python version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:266
msgid ""
"SIDE_MODULE_CFLAGS: The standard CFLAGS for a side module. Use when "
"compiling libraries or shared libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:268
msgid ""
"SIDE_MODULE_LDFLAGS: The standard LDFLAGS for a side module. Use when "
"linking a shared library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/meta-yaml.md:270
msgid ""
"NUMPY_LIB: Use `-L$NUMPY_LIB` as a ldflag when linking `-lnpymath` or `-"
"lnpyrandom`."
msgstr ""
